sets

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict sets with age, gender, previous_volunteer, number_volunteer_r, attendance and time_point (formula: sets ~ 1 + age + gender + previous_volunteer + number_volunteer_r + attendance + time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.34) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.16. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, gender = female, previous_volunteer = yes_beyong_12_month, number_volunteer_r = 0, attendance = 0 and time_point = 1st , is at 21.65 (S.E. = 2.38, p < .001, 95% CI [16.98, 26.32]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.03, S.E. = 0.03, p = 0.298, 95% CI [-0.09, 0.03]; Std. beta = -0.18, 95% CI [-0.53, 0.16])
  • The effect of gender [male] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.62, S.E. = 1.03, p = 0.549, 95% CI [-1.40, 2.64]; Std. beta = 0.26, 95% CI [-0.60, 1.12])
  • The effect of previous volunteer [yes_within_12_month] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.55, S.E. = 0.82, p = 0.507, 95% CI [-1.06, 2.16]; Std. beta = 0.23, 95% CI [-0.45, 0.92])
  • The effect of number volunteer r is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.66, S.E. = 0.49, p = 0.177, 95% CI [-0.30, 1.62]; Std. beta = 0.25, 95% CI [-0.11, 0.62])
  • The effect of attendance is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.33, S.E. = 0.41, p = 0.422, 95% CI [-1.12, 0.47]; Std. beta = -0.14, 95% CI [-0.48, 0.20])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.69, S.E. = 0.81, p = 0.395, 95% CI [-0.90, 2.29]; Std. beta = 0.30, 95% CI [-0.39, 0.98])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
